‚úçÔ∏èüìê George Saunders at Mines: Fiction, Engineering & Communication

I had the chance to hear author George Saunders speak at Colorado School of Mines last night. George is a 1981 Mines grad and is one of America‚Äôs most celebrated fiction writers. I personally love his work and will nerd-out with anyone who wants to :-)

On the surface, engineering and fiction writing don‚Äôt seem to overlap. But Saunders made two points that stuck with me:

1Ô∏è‚É£ Everything is communication.
Engineers design the bridges, planes, pipelines, and systems that shape our world. But it‚Äôs not enough to ‚Äúdo the work.‚Äù We also have a responsibility to clearly communicate options, tradeoffs, and risks to decision-makers so they can make informed choices.

2Ô∏è‚É£ Life (and writing) is drafting.
Just like an engineer revises plans or a writer revises stories, our brains are constantly drafting who we are. Sometimes we‚Äôre the impatient driver honking in traffic; sometimes we‚Äôre the family member sitting quietly at a hospital bedside. Both are ‚Äúyou.‚Äù The challenge is putting ourselves in the right situations so our better drafts show up more often.

His talk was a reminder that art and science aren‚Äôt opposites - they‚Äôre both about clarity, revision, and service to others.

IYKYK - and if not, I highly encourage giving George Saunders a read. His piece "Congratulations, by the way" is a superb, 20-min intro. I loved "A Swim in the Pond in the Rain" and "CivilWarLand in Bad Decline" - but you can't go wrong. 

#Engineering #Communication #GeorgeSaunders #Leadership #Storytelling

üí°‚è™ Recap: Silicon Flatirons Startup Variety Show 
ü´Äü©∫ Cardiac Health Tech Edition

Hosted by Silicon Flatirons and co-led by Brad Bernthal (Silicon Flatirons Center for Law, Technology, and Entrepreneurship) and Grant Besser (BOULDER COMMUNITY HEALTH FOUNDATION), the Startup Variety Show spotlighted innovations in cardiology, medical devices, and digital health, while stitching together leaders from CU Boulder, federal labs, startups, and major health tech companies.

ü§Ø Here‚Äôs what stood out from an evening packed with big ideas and even bigger potential

ü´Ä Transforming Heart Care
Dr. Srinivas Iyengar & Dr. Molly Ware from Boulder Community Health highlighted non-surgical revolutions in cardiology - devices like TAVR, Watchman, and MitraClip now treat conditions that previously required open-heart surgery. Procedures once rare (20/yr) are now performed over 100,000 times a year, saving and extending lives. 
üîÆLooking ahead: AI will improve imaging, patient matching, and post-op care.

üëÇ Vital Signs, Reinvented
Jason McGowin (VitaWave Tech Inc.) is reimagining how we measure blood pressure. The current process hasn't changed much since 1896. Their in-ear, cuffless BP monitor aims to bring vital data into patients‚Äô daily lives - without the clinic visit. Born from CU‚Äôs Embark program, this is bench-to-bedside innovation in action.
üîÆLooking ahead: Expecting mother's get reliable data without trips to the doctor.

üß† Preventing Stroke, One Device at a Time
Erin Spiegel, PhD & Kyle Carter (Transverse Medical Inc) presented a tool to catch calcified particles during aortic procedures, reducing stroke risk. Their challenge? Convincing hospitals to invest in prevention. A great audience Q: Who pays: doctors or hospitals? The answer: stroke care costs millions; prevention should be worth $5K.
üîÆLooking ahead: This product will be commercialized in 2028

üß¨ From Edge Cases to Everyday Solutions
Tim Kelley and Alexander Davis (Medtronic) walked through how interventional cardiology has moved from a ‚Äúlast resort‚Äù to the new standard. Once used only for patients who couldn‚Äôt survive surgery, Medtronic‚Äôs miniaturized, catheter-based devices are now used across risk levels - from the critically ill to low-risk populations.
üîÆLooking ahead: Improving current products for more specific use-cases, and inventing new one


üß†‚ú® Final Thought
Colorado‚Äôs health tech ecosystem is thriving. Big problems, bold teams, and deep collaboration are leading to real solutions.
Grateful to Silicon Flatirons and Colorado Law for keeping the spotlight on innovation with impact.
